  "text": "Because reversibility is a hallmark of epigenetic transcriptional suppression, we treated hypermethylated CML cells K562 with 5-aza-2Ј-deoxycytidine to attempt demethylation of CpG sites at the promoter area of the JunB gene. In the treated cells, increased JunB gene expression was observed after 24 hours and carried on for at least 5 days. In addition, decreased intensities of JunB-M PCR products and slightly increased intensities of JunB-U PCR products were also observed. The allelic patterns of CpG island methylation also revealed an increase in unmethylated sites. Results from demethylation studies demonstrated that methylation of CpG sites at the promoter area of JunB did cause the loss of JunB gene expression. However, the JunB gene expression level in cells treated with 5-aza-2Ј-deoxycytidine cells was not restored to the normal level. Consistent with the JunB gene expression, the JunB protein was increased insignificantly, which may be because the method is not sensitive enough to detect the change, and the JunB-M PCR products were slightly diminished but not fully vanished in treated cells. Previous study has demonstrated that transcription from densely methylated promoters can only be partially restored by 5-aza-2Ј-deoxycytidine treatment but can obviously be enhanced by cotreatment with an inhibitor of histone deacetylase. [CITATION_1] Therefore, another mechanism, such as deacetylation change of JunB gene, may play some role in the inactivation of the CpG island of JunB gene in K562 cells.",
